    "title": "AI & Robotics Snacks — April 21, 2026",
    "date": "2026-04-21",
    "tags": ["Meta layoffs AI capex", "TSMC Arizona 3nm", "Claude Design Figma", "Samsung Galaxy AI Glasses"],
    "fresh": true,
    "content": "**AI & Robotics Snacks** — April 21, 2026\n\n---\n\n## 💼 Meta Is Cutting 8,000 Jobs to Fund a $115B AI Bet\n\nWith $201B in 2025 revenue (+22% YoY), Meta announced it would cut 10% of its workforce — 8,000 people, effective May 20 — and redirect the savings into $115-135B of AI infrastructure in 2026, nearly doubling 2025's $72.2B capex.\n\n- **The math:** $115-135B goes to data centers, GPUs, Llama infrastructure, and a $27B joint venture with Nebius for a gigawatt-scale AI campus in Louisiana. The humans cost less than the power.\n- **The pattern:** Oracle cut 20,000-30,000 people. Meta cuts 8,000. Both reporting record quarters. Headcount is being converted directly into compute.\n\n*Best quarter in company history. Time to cut 8,000 people. The AI pivot is fully underway.*\n\n**Sources:** [The Next Web](https://thenextweb.com/news/meta-layoffs-may-2026-ai-restructuring-thousands) | [Startup Article](https://startuparticle.com/technology/2026/04/meta-to-cut-10-workforce-8000-layoffs-expected-amid-135b-ai-investment/)\n\n---\n\n## 🏭 TSMC Raised 2026 Capex to $52-56B. Arizona 3nm Ready Late 2027.\n\nTSMC Q1 2026 earnings confirmed $52-56B in capex for the year — up 27-40% from $40.9B in 2025 — driven by what the company calls a \"multiyear AI megatrend.\" Fab 21 Phase 2 in Arizona gets equipment installed in Q3 2026, with high-volume 3nm production by late 2027 — a full year ahead of the original 2028 target.\n\n- **The scale:** Arizona now covers 2,000+ acres, $165B total committed — the largest foreign direct investment in US history. Six fabs, two packaging facilities, one R&D center.\n- **The caveat:** TSMC explicitly warned the Middle East conflict and Hormuz closure may increase logistics costs and impact profitability. The world's most critical chip fab is watching the same ceasefire deadline as everyone else.\n\n*The most important chip factory in the world is being built faster. It is also watching the Strait of Hormuz.*\n\n**Sources:** [Tom's Hardware](https://www.tomshardware.com/tech-industry/semiconductors/tsmc-ups-revenue-guidance-and-capex-buoyed-by-multiyear-ai-megatrend-warns-middle-east-conflict-may-impact-profitability-as-costs-increase) | [TrendForce](https://www.trendforce.com/news/2026/04/16/news-tsmc-n3-tightens-on-ai-demand-arizona-2nd-fab-3nm-volume-production-in-2h27-kumamoto-in-2028/)\n\n---\n\n## 🎨 Anthropic Launched Claude Design. Figma Stock Immediately Dropped.\n\nOn April 17, Anthropic launched Claude Design — a tool that turns prompts into prototypes, pitch decks, wireframes, and marketing assets. Built on Claude Opus 4.7. Exports to Canva, PDF, PPTX, and standalone HTML. Rolling out to Pro, Max, Team, and Enterprise subscribers.\n\n- **The target:** Founders, product managers, and marketers who need visuals without a design team. Realistic prototypes from a chat window, no Figma skills required.\n- **The reaction:** Figma stock fell immediately after the announcement. The market read it as Anthropic entering the design tools market — and Figma as the most obvious casualty.\n\n*Anthropic launches a design tool. Figma stock falls. The AI land grab has reached design software.*\n\n**Sources:** [TechCrunch](https://techcrunch.com/2026/04/17/anthropic-launches-claude-design-a-new-product-for-creating-quick-visuals/) | [Gizmodo](https://gizmodo.com/anthropic-launches-claude-design-figma-stock-immediately-nosedives-2000748071)\n\n---\n\n## 👓 Samsung Confirms Galaxy AI Glasses for July 2026: $499 Entry, 12MP, Gemini\n\nSamsung confirmed Galaxy AI Smart Glasses launching July 2026 alongside the Galaxy Z Fold 8 and Z Flip 8. The audio/AI variant starts at $499; the MicroLED HUD model goes up to $649. Powered by Qualcomm AR1+ Gen 1, Android XR, with Gemini AI for real-time visual recognition and a 12MP camera.\n\n- **The details:** 245mAh battery (6-8 hours), voice/vision/gesture controls. Design partnerships with Warby Parker and Gentle Monster — Samsung is going fashion-first, tech-second to compete with Ray-Ban Meta.\n- **The bet:** Ray-Ban Meta became a category hit by doing less. Samsung is doing more at roughly the same price. Whether that approach resonates with consumers is the $649 question.\n\n*Ray-Ban Meta didn't have a MicroLED HUD. Galaxy Glasses will. July will tell us if that was the right call.*\n\n**Sources:** [CNBC](https://www.cnbc.com/2026/03/06/samsung-ai-smart-glasses-first-details-specs-release-date.html) | [Newsbytes](https://www.newsbytesapp.com/news/science/samsung-likely-to-unveil-galaxy-ai-smart-glasses-july-2026/tldr)"
  }
]
